## Summary
I searched the codebase for all files related to admin/super-admin settings. The admin settings feature exists but is **a stub/placeholder** — the controller validates input but does NOT persist it, and there is **no settings model and no database migration/table** for it. Below are the findings.

## 1. Controller — `app\Http\Controllers\Admin\SettingsController.php`
Full file (the relevant handler):
```php
namespace App\Http\Controllers\Admin;

use App\Http\Controllers\Controller;
use Illuminate\Http\Request;

class SettingsController extends Controller
{
    public function index()
    {
        return view('admin.settings.index');
    }

    public function update(Request $request)
    {
        // Platform settings storage (could be a key-value table or config)
        $validated = $request->validate([
            'platform_name' => 'required|string|max:255',
            'support_email' => 'required|email|max:255',
        ]);

        // For now, store in config cache or .env
        // This is a placeholder — real implementation would persist settings

        return back()->with('success', 'Settings updated successfully.');
    }
}
```
⚠️ Key finding: `update()` validates `platform_name` and `support_email` but never saves them anywhere (the validation result `$validated` is unused). Persistence is explicitly marked as a TODO.

## 2. Routes — `routes\web.php`
Imported at line 6: `use App\Http\Controllers\Admin\SettingsController;`
Registered inside the `auth` + `admin` (super_admin) middleware group, prefixed `admin` and named `admin.`:
```php
Route::middleware('admin')->prefix('admin')->name('admin.')->group(function () {
    // ...dashboard, schools, plans, payment-requests...
    Route::get('settings', [SettingsController::class, 'index'])->name('settings.index');
    Route::put('settings', [SettingsController::class, 'update'])->name('settings.update');
});
```
So the live URLs are `GET /admin/settings` and `PUT /admin/settings` (named `admin.settings.index` / `admin.settings.update`). Note: a *separate* per-school settings feature also exists under `school.` prefix using `App\Http\Controllers\School\SchoolSettingController` (different concern — persists onto the `School` model).

## 3. Blade View — `resources\views\admin\settings\index.blade.php`
`@extends('layouts.admin')`, titled "Platform Settings". Contains a form posting via `@method('PUT')` to `{{ route('admin.settings.update') }}` with two fields:
- `platform_name` (default value `EASYSOLVE`)
- `support_email` (default value `support@easysolve.com`)
Includes a "Platform Info" sidebar (version 1.0.0, environment, Laravel version) and quick links. Because the controller doesn't persist, the form always reverts to these hardcoded defaults.

## 4. Model / DB
❌ **No settings model exists.** Searched `app/Models/**/*.php` (26 models) — none named `Setting` or `AppSetting`, and no `use App\Models\Setting` / `AppSetting` imports anywhere.
❌ **No settings migration exists.** Glob `database/migrations/*setting*` returned no files. No `platform_name` / `settings_table` references found outside the controller and view.

## 5. Navigation references to the settings page (secondary)
- `resources\views\layouts\admin.blade.php` line 234 — sidebar link: `<a href="{{ route('admin.settings.index') }}" ...>` (under the "System" section), active when `request()->routeIs('admin.settings.*')`.
- `resources\views\admin\dashboard.blade.php` line 159 — dashboard card linking to `route('admin.settings.index')`.

## Key takeaway for the caller
The admin settings UI and routing are wired up and functional in terms of display, but the persistence layer is missing entirely: there is no model, no migration, and the controller discards the validated data. Implementing it would require creating a settings table/model (e.g., key-value `AppSetting`) and updating `SettingsController@update` to read/write it, plus updating the view to load saved values instead of hardcoded defaults.

